WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.049 --> 00:00:10.280
&gt;&gt;Daniel: Thank you all for coming. I'm glad
to be here with you, and I'll launch right

00:00:10.280 --> 00:00:14.310
into this and to tell you that the reason
we began with this clip, aside from giving

00:00:14.310 --> 00:00:18.590
you a sense of what the film was like, is
because it contains, or it contains three

00:00:18.590 --> 00:00:25.519
different kinds of truths that are important.
The first is the truth about what happens

00:00:25.519 --> 00:00:30.819
to, when people try to disseminate knowledge
and galvanize people to do something about

00:00:30.819 --> 00:00:33.690
this problem, which is that there's a lot
of push back.

00:00:33.690 --> 00:00:38.329
That's what I received for it when it was
Executioners, that's what anyone receives

00:00:38.329 --> 00:00:43.980
who wants to stand up and say, "The killing
must stop. We have to do something." Particularly

00:00:43.980 --> 00:00:48.530
when you say what we have to do is something
forceful. There's enormous push back because

00:00:48.530 --> 00:00:54.050
people don't want to do anything. Not everybody,
but many, including many powerful people.

00:00:54.050 --> 00:01:01.140
A second truth that you saw in this film is
in the person of Ellie Nicarambe, so it's

00:01:01.140 --> 00:01:08.350
a small-scale truth. And it's the truth of
the perpetration on the ground of these kinds

00:01:08.350 --> 00:01:16.260
of deeds or crimes, which is that at every
moment or a moment after moment, one person

00:01:16.260 --> 00:01:22.770
decides to raise his hand, looking at a victim;
it can be a man, it can be a woman, it can

00:01:22.770 --> 00:01:28.940
be a child, and he decides, or she, they're
usually men, but there are some women, decide

00:01:28.940 --> 00:01:35.110
to strike the victim and to kill the person.

00:01:35.110 --> 00:01:41.000
Overwhelmingly, victims of genocide, of mass
murder, in our time, have been felled in a

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:49.330
personalistic way with the killer facing the
victim, often bludgeoning the victim or cutting

00:01:49.330 --> 00:01:55.390
the victim with, n-, with pre-20th century
weaponry. That's why we have to keep this

00:01:55.390 --> 00:01:59.410
in mind. The small-scale truth about the reality
of what happens.

00:01:59.410 --> 00:02:07.920
And then, there's a large-scale truth that
you saw, which is the enormity of the problem.

00:02:07.920 --> 00:02:13.980
Genocide has taken more victims than conventional
military operations during our time. Indeed,

00:02:13.980 --> 00:02:22.250
many, many more -- it's not even close. This
fact should be known to every concerned citizen

00:02:22.250 --> 00:02:27.730
of our country and indeed of all countries.
And it is a fact, which is unknown to virtually

00:02:27.730 --> 00:02:32.170
every single citizen of our country and the
rest of the world.

00:02:32.170 --> 00:02:39.730
And when you hear this, it changes the way
you see the world. War, which is at the center

00:02:39.730 --> 00:02:47.120
of international security concerns and policy-making
and at the center of the concerns of international

00:02:47.120 --> 00:02:55.110
political institutions, should be side by
side with the prevention or stopping of genocide.

00:02:55.110 --> 00:03:00.040
Which, right now, is treated as a secondary
or tertiary phenomenon, certainly not central

00:03:00.040 --> 00:03:03.650
to international security discussions or policy-making.

00:03:03.650 --> 00:03:10.541
So, this large-scale fact should change how
you understand the world and what is a, the

00:03:10.541 --> 00:03:20.180
chief problem of lethal violence in the world
today -- it's mass murder. Now to talk about

00:03:20.180 --> 00:03:25.630
this, as you have probably gleaned, my manner
is to be, to, just to be forceful. I don't

00:03:25.630 --> 00:03:34.380
sugarcoat things. It's a very serious subject
I need hardly say, but I can't in this af-,

00:03:34.380 --> 00:03:38.959
in this afternoon tell you everything that
you need to know that needs to be reconceptualized

00:03:38.959 --> 00:03:42.099
or explicated.

00:03:42.099 --> 00:03:46.790
If this were to be a full presentation, I
would go over how genocides begin -- why they

00:03:46.790 --> 00:03:54.920
actually begin. Why they unfold in the ways
they do, why the perpetrators kill. What the

00:03:54.920 --> 00:03:56.400
perpetrators' communities are like.

00:03:56.400 --> 00:04:02.020
They're not atomized people. They live in
communities while they're killing and in larger

00:04:02.020 --> 00:04:09.260
communities they are embedded, so what those
communities are like. How genocides end? A

00:04:09.260 --> 00:04:16.120
critical topic, virtually unexplored. Why
different genocides issue in different outcomes.

00:04:16.120 --> 00:04:20.000
Sometimes, mainly men are killed, sometimes
men, women and children. The numbers vary

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:25.770
enormously. Lots of things vary. Why do they
vary? And ultimately what we can do about

00:04:25.770 --> 00:04:31.270
it. Full treatment of genocide would deal
with all these subjects.

00:04:31.270 --> 00:04:37.139
I will touch on some of them, but not all
of them and if you have questions about the

00:04:37.139 --> 00:04:41.509
others, I'll be happy to hear them or your
comments, for that matter. Now the truth,

00:04:41.509 --> 00:04:44.990
and I will sit here and I will stand here
today and I will tell you what I think are

00:04:44.990 --> 00:04:53.599
truths about genocide -- things that are undeniably
true. And that that often are, though they

00:04:53.599 --> 00:05:01.490
are often contested or, or denied. It is not,
we must tell the truth about genocide.

00:05:01.490 --> 00:05:05.639
The most fundamental truth is it's not, it
is not something that is overwhelming, not

00:05:05.639 --> 00:05:10.800
beyond our understanding or beyond our control.
This is how it's often portrayed in the media

00:05:10.800 --> 00:05:16.139
and in conversation. These eruptions occur,
what can you do? These people just kill each

00:05:16.139 --> 00:05:22.219
other, what can you do? It's inevitable. It
will be with us for all of, for all time.

00:05:22.219 --> 00:05:26.840
It's endemic to the human condition and so
on. These are the things that you hear or

00:05:26.840 --> 00:05:30.889
the subtext of what is said about it. It's
simply not true. None of that is true.

00:05:30.889 --> 00:05:33.550
[audience member clears throat]

00:05:33.550 --> 00:05:38.409
It is as understandable as anything else.
It is within our control to do something about

00:05:38.409 --> 00:05:43.689
it. We need political design, political will,
political ingenuity to do it. In fact, we

00:05:43.689 --> 00:05:48.400
understand quite well why these things happen
and, I think, what we can do about them.

00:05:48.400 --> 00:05:53.630
We need to tell the truth about the extent
of the problem. It's not just the numbers

00:05:53.630 --> 00:05:59.620
that I've told you. We have to recognize that
this is a systemic feature of the modern world.

00:05:59.620 --> 00:06:05.240
As bad as you think the Rwanda or the former
Yugoslavia or the Holocaust or Darfur or name

00:06:05.240 --> 00:06:11.400
whatever genocide that you want. As bad as
you think that that is, these are typically

00:06:11.400 --> 00:06:17.860
portrayed as a series of w-, unrelated one-off
events when, in fact, they are systemic features

00:06:17.860 --> 00:06:23.900
of the internation-or-of the international
community or of the world order. Systematically

00:06:23.900 --> 00:06:26.180
produced, we need to begin to see them that
way.

00:06:26.180 --> 00:06:31.580
And the reason it's important is if you see
it as a systemic problem, than you begin to

00:06:31.580 --> 00:06:36.819
think about systemic solutions and not just
waiting till the next one happens and say,

00:06:36.819 --> 00:06:40.729
"What can we do here? What should we do? What
ought we do?" And either do it or more likely

00:06:40.729 --> 00:06:44.479
not.

00:06:44.479 --> 00:06:49.069
And, as I said, it must become a central feature
because it's systemic to world. The extent

00:06:49.069 --> 00:06:55.021
of the problem is so great of international
security policy making. We must tell the truth

00:06:55.021 --> 00:07:00.169
about the nature of the problem. The problem,
as bad as it is, is namely genocide, is not

00:07:00.169 --> 00:07:07.039
even the real problem. It's not the most fundamental
problem. Genocide is but one manifestation

00:07:07.039 --> 00:07:16.279
of, of more fundamental kind of politics,
which can be called eliminationism.

00:07:16.279 --> 00:07:20.119
Eliminationism takes many forms, and it is
what it sounds like. It's a politics in which

00:07:20.119 --> 00:07:25.059
states and the people supporting them, it's
almost always states, decide to eliminate

00:07:25.059 --> 00:07:31.819
a group of people. That's the politics. The
reasons it is done vary from case to case.

00:07:31.819 --> 00:07:36.999
It's something we could talk about. I'm not
going to get into now.

00:07:36.999 --> 00:07:42.029
When they decide to eliminate a group, they
then choose a variety of eliminations means,

00:07:42.029 --> 00:07:49.619
or eliminations tools to employ. And they
include force transformation, so forcing people

00:07:49.619 --> 00:07:56.740
to convert from their religion, for example,
force transformation, incarceration in camps,

00:07:56.740 --> 00:08:01.650
the prevention of a group's reproduction,
which is often done through sexual violence

00:08:01.650 --> 00:08:10.599
 -- rape. Expelling people and slaughtering
them, en mass, the largest such slaughters

00:08:10.599 --> 00:08:15.599
of what we typically call genocide.

00:08:15.599 --> 00:08:19.629
Now, the reason to look at the problem of
the politics of eliminationism as a federal

00:08:19.629 --> 00:08:24.169
problem and not genocide, itself, is not just
because that really is what's going on. States

00:08:24.169 --> 00:08:27.719
decide to do this, their followers say, "Oh,
yes, we have to get rid of these people,"

00:08:27.719 --> 00:08:33.630
and then they carry it out. But also because
in every case of what we call genocide, the

00:08:33.630 --> 00:08:39.380
perpetrators have used some of these, if not
all, these other eliminationist means at the

00:08:39.380 --> 00:08:44.331
same time. And when you see that, you see
that genocide really is but a policy tool.

00:08:44.331 --> 00:08:48.440
Or mass murder is a policy tool that goes
along with these other ones. So, we have to

00:08:48.440 --> 00:08:53.870
start focusing on not just stopping the killing,
but on all forms of elimination politics and

00:08:53.870 --> 00:09:01.290
come up with an anti-eliminationist political
response.

00:09:01.290 --> 00:09:06.570
We need to tell the truth about the perpetrators.
They're not abstractions, they're not blindly

00:09:06.570 --> 00:09:12.190
obedient as is often said to authority, they're
not just pressured to do what they do because

00:09:12.190 --> 00:09:16.990
of the system, they're not bureaucrats as
they're often, as they have often been portrayed

00:09:16.990 --> 00:09:22.800
 -- just doing what bureaucrats do, which
is supposedly a job well done.

00:09:22.800 --> 00:09:28.970
They are, as I told you earlier, they're individual
human beings working to get, working together,

00:09:28.970 --> 00:09:33.990
but each one deciding what to do to raise
his hand, making decisions about what's right

00:09:33.990 --> 00:09:38.470
and wrong -- knowing, having views about what's
right or wrong, and wrong. One thing that's

00:09:38.470 --> 00:09:42.100
not in the film, I don't if, how many of you
have seen the film or if you're going to,

00:09:42.100 --> 00:09:50.199
but one thing that is not in the film is in
Rwanda, we went to the war camp of the people

00:09:50.199 --> 00:09:55.769
you saw in the opening clip. And it was early
afternoon, they'd finished their day of work,

00:09:55.769 --> 00:10:00.000
they were having lunch and their lunch was
in a large shed. It was about 50 yards or

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:07.529
60 yards by 30 yards and there were benches,
so it's a rather big, a rather big place.

00:10:07.529 --> 00:10:09.420
And their bench is in a parabolic form.

00:10:09.420 --> 00:10:15.319
Actually, not very different from here. And,
and I went in there with the director of photography,

00:10:15.319 --> 00:10:19.290
and I was standing not very different from
where I'm standing now at the point, at the

00:10:19.290 --> 00:10:23.649
focal point of the parabola, and there were
no guards in this camp. It was a minimum-security

00:10:23.649 --> 00:10:29.769
c-, camp, I will get, I can tell you later
why, and I looked out on a scene, a surrealistic

00:10:29.769 --> 00:10:35.089
scene of the kind that I never imagined in
my life I would see. Which is, a thousand

00:10:35.089 --> 00:10:38.870
mass murderers, or a thousand people there,
mostly men, a few women.

00:10:38.870 --> 00:10:43.410
A thousand mass murderers and they were all
staring at us. They didn't look very happy.

00:10:43.410 --> 00:10:50.440
We've later found out they weren't very happy.
And I thought to myself, "Look at these people."

00:10:50.440 --> 00:10:55.050
And that we have to humanize them. They're
not a mass of people; they're an individual

00:10:55.050 --> 00:11:03.040
mass murderer, a thousand times over, who
individually and collectively decided to work

00:11:03.040 --> 00:11:10.480
in concert to slaughter their victims. We
need to humanize them. And part of that is

00:11:10.480 --> 00:11:17.110
recognizing that, as other human beings have
done -- they can make decisions based on their

00:11:17.110 --> 00:11:19.379
values to slaughter people.

00:11:19.379 --> 00:11:23.759
[Daniel coughs]

00:11:23.759 --> 00:11:32.009
Listen to Anne, a Tutsi survivor, captured,
hiding in the bush as Hutu used dogs to ferret

00:11:32.009 --> 00:11:41.390
every last Tutsi out. She, I'm, she say that,
"They slashed my right arm. Then while they

00:11:41.390 --> 00:11:50.629
were," thank you. I've reached that age. "Then
while, she had to watch as a Hutu killed all

00:11:50.629 --> 00:11:55.440
my children in front of me and they slashed
my right arm. Then," and these are her words,

00:11:55.440 --> 00:11:59.490
"while they were raping me, they were saying
that they wanted to kill all Tutsis."

00:11:59.490 --> 00:12:03.681
This is what the perpetrators were saying.
They wanted to do it. So then in the future,

00:12:03.681 --> 00:12:08.810
all that would be left would be drawings to
show that there were once a people called

00:12:08.810 --> 00:12:14.430
Tutsi. And why do the Hutu want to obliterate
the Tutsis? So they wanted to, but why did

00:12:14.430 --> 00:12:21.829
they want to do it? Ellie Nicarambe, whom
you've seen, explains that the killers did

00:12:21.829 --> 00:12:27.379
not know that the Tutsi were human beings,
because if they had thought about that, they

00:12:27.379 --> 00:12:30.189
wouldn't have killed them.

00:12:30.189 --> 00:12:34.889
"Let me also include myself." He says this
about himself as well. "Let me also include

00:12:34.889 --> 00:12:41.769
myself as someone who accepted it. I wouldn't
have accepted that the Tutsi are human beings."

00:12:41.769 --> 00:12:49.040
He's emphatic about this being the common
view and common knowledge among all Hutu.

00:12:49.040 --> 00:12:54.769
"As I was hearing it," he explains, "I had
the same perception as others at the time."

00:12:54.769 --> 00:12:59.949
Adding, that is was such a fact of Hutu society,
that no Hutu, and these are his words, "Could

00:12:59.949 --> 00:13:06.420
swear and lie to you that he did not know
that." What's the effect of such views? So

00:13:06.420 --> 00:13:10.060
they wanna do it, they wanna do it because
they have these views. What's the effect of

00:13:10.060 --> 00:13:18.670
the views upon the killers? And Nicarmbe explains,
"It is a cloud that came into people's hearts

00:13:18.670 --> 00:13:23.759
and covered them and everything became dark.
Because to see someone standing in front of

00:13:23.759 --> 00:13:29.470
you without any energy, and you hold your
machete on, your machete high, or a club and

00:13:29.470 --> 00:13:35.990
hit him, it is something difficult that was
done with a lot of anger and rage. I mean,

00:13:35.990 --> 00:13:37.759
this genocide."

00:13:37.759 --> 00:13:42.550
The perpetrators of genocide overwhelmingly
are willful killers believing what they're;

00:13:42.550 --> 00:13:46.389
that what they're doing is right and necessary.
How they came to do it, or how they're gonna

00:13:46.389 --> 00:13:50.629
do it in different instances of genocide is
more complicated, and it varies from case

00:13:50.629 --> 00:13:51.629
to case.

00:13:51.629 --> 00:13:57.710
And what they actually believe varies quite
a lot, but this is the core of it. One of

00:13:57.710 --> 00:14:01.740
the things I focus on in the film and in the
book as well is the cruelty of the perpetrators,

00:14:01.740 --> 00:14:06.040
which is almost always left out of the analysis.
The cruelty is almost endemic, almost, not,

00:14:06.040 --> 00:14:12.040
not entirely to mass murder and genocide.
Why are the perpetrators so unnecessarily

00:14:12.040 --> 00:14:17.670
cruel to their victims? Torturing them, beating
them, degrading them in ways that are not

00:14:17.670 --> 00:14:22.040
necessary for the simple act of killing.

00:14:22.040 --> 00:14:28.310
The truth is that we need to em-, to humanize
not just the perpetrators, but also the victims.

00:14:28.310 --> 00:14:36.310
Now, this may surprise you because we all
empathize with the victims. When we think

00:14:36.310 --> 00:14:43.699
about them, we can have some sense, some sense,
of the suffering and the horror that they

00:14:43.699 --> 00:14:44.699
endured.

00:14:44.699 --> 00:14:50.680
But we need to humanize them because we lose
their individuality in the numbers. A thousand

00:14:50.680 --> 00:14:56.230
people are, the perpetrators kill a thousand
people here, 400 thousand there, millions

00:14:56.230 --> 00:15:01.680
here; it's easy to lose the individuality
of each of the victims. I have sat across,

00:15:01.680 --> 00:15:05.910
stood across, walked with victims from genocides
arou--

00:15:05.910 --> 00:15:09.120
[Daniel coughs and clears throat]

00:15:09.120 --> 00:15:10.120
Excuse me.

00:15:10.120 --> 00:15:11.120
[Daniel coughs]

00:15:11.120 --> 00:15:16.490
from genocides or mass eliminations around
the world. You hear their stories, you see

00:15:16.490 --> 00:15:23.459
their suffering; these are the ones who ar-,
who survived. They are marked, indelibly,

00:15:23.459 --> 00:15:29.720
with horror and suffering for their whole
lives. We need to do it. And the reason we

00:15:29.720 --> 00:15:36.290
need to do it is because it is focusing on
what they are going through, and imagining

00:15:36.290 --> 00:15:40.160
what it would be like for any of us or our
family members to go through it, which will

00:15:40.160 --> 00:15:45.100
motivate us and motivate our political leaders
if we can get them to start thinking this

00:15:45.100 --> 00:15:50.899
way, to do something to stop it or prevent
it. So, we need to humanize the victims because

00:15:50.899 --> 00:15:57.759
it's the right thing to do and because it's
the politically important thing to do.

00:15:57.759 --> 00:16:00.149
We need to tell the truth about what starts
genocides.

00:16:00.149 --> 00:16:03.230
[Daniel coughs]

00:16:03.230 --> 00:16:08.970
It's not ethnic con-, it's not ethnic conflict.
It's not hatred spun out of control. It's

00:16:08.970 --> 00:16:14.680
not all of the structural or transhistorical
factors that are often said to start genocides.

00:16:14.680 --> 00:16:20.689
All these things may go in to creating the
conditions under which they begin, but ultimately,

00:16:20.689 --> 00:16:28.850
almost every genocide has begun because one
person or small group of people have made

00:16:28.850 --> 00:16:34.050
a decision to slaughter or otherwise eliminate
the victims.

00:16:34.050 --> 00:16:36.680
[Daniel coughs]

00:16:36.680 --> 00:16:39.910
We can name these people. We often know when
the decision was taken.

00:16:39.910 --> 00:16:44.790
[Daniel clear throat]

00:16:44.790 --> 00:16:53.709
Excuse me. All the things that are necessary
for genocides to occur, such as a willing

00:16:53.709 --> 00:16:57.709
population of perpetrators who will carry
out the orders and they have found them, but

00:16:57.709 --> 00:17:07.780
if this decision is not taken, if Hitler or
Pol Pot or Bagosora or Milosevic or al-Bashir,

00:17:07.780 --> 00:17:18.830
decided not to initiate mass slaughter, eliminationism
or genocide, it would not happen. And they

00:17:18.830 --> 00:17:23.180
could've always, in every instance, decided
to do otherwise.

00:17:23.180 --> 00:17:26.500
This is critically important to recognize
because when you shift the discussion away

00:17:26.500 --> 00:17:32.890
from this abstraction, such as ethnic conflict
or transhistorical forces or globalization

00:17:32.890 --> 00:17:37.340
or capitalism, or whatever you want to say,
and you start focusing on the human beings

00:17:37.340 --> 00:17:43.220
who actually make the decisions, you can begin
to think very differently about policy responses.

00:17:43.220 --> 00:17:48.300
And how to make other leaders, the future
or would-be genocidal leaders make other decisions

00:17:48.300 --> 00:17:49.300
in the future.

00:17:49.300 --> 00:17:51.960
[Daniel clears throat]

00:17:51.960 --> 00:17:57.340
And this brings us back to the problem of
politics. It begins because political leaders

00:17:57.340 --> 00:18:07.050
have political goals of social transformation,
of dominance, power, of creating a utopia

00:18:07.050 --> 00:18:14.310
as they understand it, of gaining or maintaining
territory, or what have you.

00:18:14.310 --> 00:18:21.250
It's politics and we need to reinsert or recapture
genocide eliminationism into our understanding

00:18:21.250 --> 00:18:24.760
of politics, which is has been sequestered
from. It's treated as something that sort

00:18:24.760 --> 00:18:30.400
of out of this world. It's another form of
politics; a politics of eliminationism, which

00:18:30.400 --> 00:18:38.250
is on a continuum with other kinds of repressive
and even normal politics. It's politics, which

00:18:38.250 --> 00:18:40.240
we can meet with politics.

00:18:40.240 --> 00:18:43.520
We must tell the truth about what we do, which
is next to nothing.

00:18:43.520 --> 00:18:46.680
[Daniel clears throat]

00:18:46.680 --> 00:18:51.990
Really, next to nothing. We stand by and watch
as people get slaughtered, expelled, raped,

00:18:51.990 --> 00:18:57.450
otherwise brutalized. And we need to tell
the truth about why we do nothing because

00:18:57.450 --> 00:19:03.410
of cynicism of our political leaders, which
are, who are governed by the hallowed creation

00:19:03.410 --> 00:19:08.560
of national interest. That is, we only do
something that is within our nation's interests,

